        <div id="post-19784041628" class="post post-type-text">
            <div class="post-meta">
            
                <div class="date">
                    March 23, 2012
                </div><!-- .date -->
            
            </div><!-- .post-meta -->
            <div class="post-content">
            
                <h4><a href="https://news.gain.org/post/19784041628/business-and-local-governments-highlight-water-stress">Business and Local Governments Highlight Water Stress in Congressional Briefing</a></h4>
                <p><p class="MsoNormal"><a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/globalai/7065830751/" title="IMGP0025 by GlobalAdaptation, on Flickr"><img align="right" alt="IMGP0025" height="180" src="https://farm8.staticflickr.com/7074/7065830751_3ece9fde7e_m.jpg" width="240"/></a><span>On March 20, the private sector and representatives from state water agencies joined together to address their respective adaptation approaches to the impacts of climate change and population growth on the U.S. water and wastewater infrastructure. <span> </span>The briefing, <em>Water Utility Resiliency and Sustainability: How Water Utilities are Managing the Country’s Vital Water Resources in the Wake of Changing Hydrologic Conditions</em>, took place in the Congressional Cannon House Office Building in Washington, D.C.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span><!-- more --></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>Kathy Freas, Global Service Team Director/Water Business Group for </span><a href="https://www.ch2m.com/corporate/markets/water/default.asp"><span>CH2M Hill</span></a><span>, moderated a panel of leading water management experts across the country. Unique challenges exist for each of these regional water systems — the southwest must contend with dramatic declines in water levels while New York City is managing water quality problems associated with increased flooding and storm intensity. Nationally, all regions may face increased disruptions to water supplies through sea level rise, higher energy demands and declining water quality. </span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>Freas highlighted the potential investments needed in US water infrastructu</span><a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/robbyb/2639462/" title="Hoover Dam by robbyb, on Flickr"><img align="right" alt="Hoover Dam" height="180" src="https://farm1.staticflickr.com/2/2639462_90c862f657_m.jpg" width="240"/></a><span>re through 2050, which could amount to between </span><a href="https://www.georgetownclimate.org/resources/confronting-climate-change-an-early-analysis-of-water-and-wastewater-adaptation-costs"><span>$448 billion to $944 billion</span></a><span>. Such investments include:</span></p>
<ul type="disc"><li class="MsoNormal"><span>increasing water storage capacity;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal"><span>building more water treatment facilities;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal"><span>using new water sources, such as seawater though desalination plants;</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal"><span>implementing greater effluent treatment and recycling processes; and</span></li>
<li class="MsoNormal"><span>guarding against increased flooding and storm surges.</span></li>
</ul><p class="MsoNormal"><span>Panelists also highlighted the </span><a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/hr2738"><em><span>Water Infrastructure Resiliency and Sustainability Act</span></em></a><span>, federal legislation that would establish funds to support adaptation strategies for the U.S. water supply, wastewater, stormwater and flood management infrastructure. Congress has not taken significant action on the bill thus far. </span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>Investments in national water infrastructure will take a concerted effort from both the private and public sectors. While legislation stalls in Congress, companies such as CH2M Hill are already helping the nation to adapt by providing </span><a href="https://www.ch2m.com/corporate/markets/water/ecosystem.asp"><span>adaptation planning services</span></a><span>, wastewater infrastructure and drinking water treatment facilities.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>*</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span>Photo1: Kathy Freas, </span><span>Global Service Team Director/Water Business Group for </span><span>CH2M Hill</span><span>.</span></p></p>
                
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
